e named Deighton, from Old English <i>dīc</i> ‘ditch, dike’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement, enclosure’. See also   Ditton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ditton","meanings":["English (Kent): habitational name from any of numerous places called Ditton, for example Ditton in Kent, Buckinghamshire, and Lancashire; Fen Ditton or Wood Ditton in Cambridgeshire; or Thames Ditton or Long Ditton in Surrey, all from Old English <i>dīc</i> ‘ditch, dike’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement, farmstead’."]},{"name":"Deaton","meanings":["English (Middlesex): variant of   Deighton  ."]},{"name":"Dinsdale","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from Over Dinsdale (North Yorkshire) or Low Dinsdale (Durham), which stand on opposite sides of the Tees river. The name arises from Old English <i>Dīctūneshalh</i> ‘nook, recess (Old English <i>halh</i>) belonging to   Deighton  ’."]},{"name":"Deyton","meanings":["English: variant of   Deighton  ."]},{"name":"Dighton","meanings":["English (Huntingdonshire): variant of   Deighton  ."]},{"name":"Dayton","meanings":["English: variant of   Deighton  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Deighton was born in 1260, in Deighton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Thomas De Deighton, was 26 and her mother, Mrs. Thomas de Deighton or Dicton, was 22. She married John De Stainton in 1279, in Stainton, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 5 sons. She died in December 1316, in Stainton, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1260–Dec 1316":"1260–detsember 1316","1260–1316":"1260–1316","1255–1290":"1255–1290","1240–1290":"1240–1290","1280–1330":"1280–1330","1282–Male":"1282–Surnud","1284–Male":"1284–Surnud","1286–Male":"1286–Surnud","1289–1330":"1289–1330","1235–1280":"1235–1280","1239–Female":"1239–Surnud","1286":"1286","1330":"1330","1284":"1284","Dec 1316":"detsember 1316","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1239":"1239","1316":"1316","1279":"1279","1235":"1235","1289":"1289","1255":"1255","Stainton, North Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Stainton, Yorkshire, England","Deighton, Yorkshire, England":"Deighton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Moorhouse, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Woolley, Yorkshire, England":"Woolley, Yorkshire, England","Stainton, Westmorland, England":"Stainton, Westmorland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1260–Dec 1316":"1260–joulukuu 1316","1260–1316":"1260–1316","1255–1290":"1255–1290","1240–1290":"1240–1290","1280–1330":"1280–1330","1282–Male":"1282–Kuollut","1284–Male":"1284–Kuollut","1286–Male":"1286–Kuollut","1289–1330":"1289–1330","1235–1280":"1235–1280